As the people of Indonesia's Aceh province try to rebuild lives shattered by the tsunami disaster, officials are also assessing the environmental damage to the coast which bore the brunt of the giant waves.
Coastlines that have proven tragically vulnerable to tsunamis should nurture healthy coral reefs, beds of sea grass and mangrove swamps, which are natural buffers against killer waves, speakers at the UN-backed biodiversity forum said.
